  "prompt": "Which country does the prime minister/president have the least power over the country?",
  "response": "It's difficult to definitively state which country has the least powerful prime minister or president, as this can vary based on constitutional structure and specific circumstances. However, some countries with notably limited executive power include:\n\n1. Switzerland - Has a unique system with a collective presidency (Federal Council) where power is shared among seven members\n\n2. Germany - The Chancellor's power is significantly constrained by the parliamentary system and strong constitutional checks\n\n3. Netherlands - The Prime Minister has relatively limited executive authority compared to other European countries\n\n4. Belgium - Has a complex federal system with power distributed among different regional governments\n\n5. Israel - Frequent coalition governments and a parliamentary system limit prime ministerial power\n\nThe specific power dynamics can change over time and depend on various political factors. The degree of executive power is influenced by:\n- Constitutional framework\n- Separation of powers\n- Parliamentary vs. presidential systems\n- Political culture\n- Strength of democratic institutions\n\nEach country's system has unique characteristics, so a definitive ranking is challenging. Academic and political science research would provide more nuanced insights into comparative executive power.",
